Summary¶

The project that I propose uses the twitter Internet Research Agency dataset released in October of 2018. The data is fairly new and, as yet, has not had much work done with it. Linvill and Warren have a pending article that categorizes these trolls (using data that they collected) into researcher-labeled categories. Their aim was "to better understand the IRA's agenda building campaign." I think that it's vitally important to understand how information, especially misinformation, spreads from person to person. My goal is to create a project that not only examines the conceptual structure of these troll's work, but allows a user to contextualize their own public textual history (tweets) within those structures. I plan to conduct this analysis in two ways: 1) use Latent Semantic Mapping (via Jerome Bellegarda) to analyze the latent conceptual structure of the IRA tweets and 2) develop social networks based on conceptual similarities that will allow us (analysts) to find those accounts that work as bridges between conceptually coherent groups. Finding these bridge nodes and then analyzing the structure of their tweets should give us insight into what makes them function as bridges between these groups and how information becomes amenable to outside groups. My analysis, via Jupyter notebook, focuses only on those tweets whose language was English (as did Linvill and Warren) for the sake of time and ease of sharing, but I believe that the LSM model would accommodate those tweets in languages that are not English and could make use of the entire data set. In the future, I would like to create a web application that allows a user to enter their own twitter handle, retrieve their tweets, and find which trolls are most aligned with their own tweets, what terms in the corpus most closely represent their twitter behavior, and what their network looks like within the IRA corpus. Each user's input has the potential to expand the corpus as a whole and to allow us to continually learn about the way that information is disseminated. The entire data set is 5.312 GB; I used python to create and analyze a subset (those tweets whose language was indicated to be English) which was 1.597 GB. My subset of the data was used to derive a term-document sparse matrix with users being considered documents and subsequently 3 matrices generated by Singular Value Decomposition. There are 473,486 unique terms and 3,259 users (a matrix of 473,486x3259). I think the application of this project is broad but would be most at home in creating better suggestion engines (who to follow, for example, being based on the contents of your tweets rather than who you know or your self-selected interests), the dissemination of important public information (who needs to see a health advisory first to make sure the most possible people see it), and, likewise, targeted marketing.

Deliverables¶

This section will describe the deliverables, both immediate and intended.

Immediate¶

  • Jupyter notebook with exploratory analysis and graphics. ### Future
  • Web application that allows users to input their own twitter handle to see where their tweets position them within the corpus of IRA tweets and provides them with a categorical lable based on Linvill & Warren's categories.
  • In future, I would like to include non-english tweet data.

Basic Structure¶

This project will treat each user as if they were a book and all of their tweets combined as that book's content. Treating them in this way will allow us to analyze them as if they were a large corpus of text and to use methods like Latent Semantic Mapping as described by Jerome Bellegarda in Latent Semantic Mapping: Principles & Applications. By treating users as authors and their combined tweets as documents, we can develop connections between users (and their bodies of tweets) based on the underlying conceptual structure of their expressions; in doing so we create social networks based not on user choice but on the content of their public expressions. We can, thereby, find potential connections that are not just recommendations, but are based on actual measures of similarity of, at least public, thought.

The Data¶

The data has been collected from Twitter's October 2018 release of IRA tweet data (found here). Below, we'll be making some changes to the data and incorporating Linvill and Warren's categorical data (found here). We'll also be filtering the data out for users whose tweets are non-english (as did Linvill & Warren).

Cleaning and Preparing the Data¶

The following code takes the data from 'ira_tweets_csv_hashed.csv' (5.312 GB), selects out only those tweets that were written in English(.1.597 GB). It then creates a term-document matrix that consists of the frequencies of all words in each user's entire tweet history (as represented by this data set). It then stores all that data as a sparse matrix to save memory and stores the values of the Singular Value Decomposition of the matrix in three csv files (u.csv, v.csv, and s.csv).

Important Running this code will fail unless ira_tweets_csv_hashed.csv exists in a folder above this one called data. Given the file size, it's difficult to include in this notebook. It can be scraped from here.

    print(f'Cleaning terms of length: {len(com)}')

    cleanCom = re.sub(r'http\S+', '', cleanCom).split(" ")
    cleanCom = sorted([w for w in cleanCom if w.lower() not in stops])

    return(cleanCom)

Analyzing the Data¶

We're going to be using Latent Semantic Mapping to examine the underlying conceptual makeup of the collected tweets of each user. First we'll load the data from files generated in the data preparation phase. In order to perform operations we need at least u, s, v, columns, and users. u maps to the term vector space of the overall model, v to the composition space, and s is the eigenvectors of the two and is used to reconstruct the original matrix/model. columns are the unique terms in the vector space and act as an index to u; likewise users is the unique list of userids and user_screen_names that act as the index to v (the compositions, if you will).

Cosine Distance¶

Cosine distance provides a good measure of distance between vectors (terms or compositions) by normalizing the lengths of the vectors. Measures like Euclidean distance are too sensitive to the magnitude of vectors and, thus, a term or composition whose structure is similar to another may be excluded because it happens to have a smaller magnitude than another. Cosine similarity measures the angle between two term vectors (for example) in the corpus and thus considers the contexts in which the term appears more fully rather than the raw frequency of the terms across the corpus.

The measures presented here are based on the cosine distance between vectors.

In [5]:
# Caluclate the Cosine Distance between two vectors.
def cosine(x,y):
    top = dot(x,y)
    bottom = np.sqrt((x*x).sum()) * np.sqrt((y*y).sum())
    cos = top/bottom
    acos = degrees(np.arccos(cos))  # Take the inverse cosine and convert from radians to degrees.
                                    # This, according to Bellegarda, satisfies the properties of a distance
                                    # in the feature space.
    return(acos)

Comparing a term within the Corpus to another term¶

How similarly are particular terms used within the feature space of the IRA tweets? How do these trolls employ concepts like immegration? We can measure something like this by examining the distance between terms like "alien" (a right-leaning way of describing immigrants) and "immegrant" (the left-leaning counterpart). To do this, we take the cosine distance of the vectors of each term in u (the cosine(UiS, UjS)).

In [2]:
def wordToWord(u, s, termOne, termTwo, columns):
    termOne = columns.index([termOne])
    termTwo = columns.index([termTwo])
    us = dot(u, np.diag(s))
    dist = cosine(us[termOne,], us[termTwo,])
    return(dist)
In [9]:
wordToWord(u,s, "alien", "immigrant", columns)
Out[9]:
28.547030975529076

The angle between the two vectors in the corpus (28.54703) seems to indicate that the two terms were use in much the same way across the corpus of trolls.

A Term to All Terms We can determine the top n terms that are similar to a given term as well.

In [49]:
def mostSimilarTerms(u,s, term, columns, numTerms):
    term = columns.index([term])
    us = dot(u,np.diag(s))
    values = {}
    # Skipping first index of columns since it's empty
    for i in range(1, u.shape[0]):
        dist = 0
        if(i != term):
            dist = cosine(us[term,], us[i,])
            if dist > 0 :
                values[columns[i][0]] = dist
    values = sorted(values.items(), key=lambda kv: kv[1])[0:numTerms]
    return values

Comparing Two Users¶

What about comparing two users within the troll corpus to determine how similar their overall tweeting behavior is to another? We'll try blackmattersus, a more-than-likely left-leaning troll, versus TEN_GOP. Linvill and Warren categorize TEN_GOP as a right troll. Where are they in the LSM space?

In [51]:
def userToUser(v,s,userOne,userTwo, users=pd.read_csv("users.csv")):
    userOne = users.loc[users.screenName == userOne].index[0]
    userTwo = users.loc[users.screenName == userTwo].index[0]
    # need to transpose v to get the v matrix and do the dot product since v is already transposed from SVD.
    vs = dot(transpose(v),np.diag(s))
    return(cosine(vs[userOne,], vs[userTwo,]))

Overall, these two accounts functioned in much the same way. We can understand, then, that the trolls operating each account sought to manipulate each side in similar ways.

def userToAll(v,s,user, numUsers, users = pd.read_csv("users.csv")):
    user = users.loc[users.screenName == user].index[0]
    values = {}
    vs = dot(transpose(v),np.diag(s))
    for i in range(0, v.shape[1]):
        dist = 0
        if(i != user):
            dist = cosine(vs[user,], vs[i,])
            if dist > 0 :
                values[users.screenName[i]] = dist
    values = sorted(values.items(), key=lambda kv: kv[1])[0:numUsers]
    return(values)

def wordToUser(u,s,v, term, user, columns, users = pd.read_csv("users.csv")):
    v = transpose(v)
    term = columns.index([term])
    user = users.loc[users.screenName == user].index[0]
    us = dot(u, np.sqrt(np.diag(s)))
    vs = dot(v, np.sqrt(np.diag(s)))
    dist = cosine(us[term,], vs[user,])
    return(dist)

def wordToAllUsers(u,s,v, term, columns, numUsers, users = pd.read_csv("users.csv")):
    v = transpose(v)
    us = dot(u, np.sqrt(np.diag(s)))
    vs = dot(v, np.sqrt(np.diag(s)))
    term = columns.index([term])
    values = {}
    for user in users.screenName:
        sn = user
        user = users.loc[users.screenName == user].index[0]
        dist = cosine(us[term,], vs[user,])
        if(dist > 0):
            values[sn] = dist
    values = sorted(values.items(), key=lambda kv: kv[1])[0:numUsers]
    return(values)

User to Words What words are most similar to a particular user? Let's look at TEN_GOP again. Since their are 473,486 terms in the corpus, this takes some time.

def userToWords(u,s,v, user, columns, numWords, users = pd.read_csv("users.csv")):
    v = transpose(v)
    us = dot(u, np.sqrt(np.diag(s)))
    vs = dot(v, np.sqrt(np.diag(s)))
    user = users.loc[users.screenName == user].index[0]
    values = {}
    for term in columns:
        if(term != []):
            i = columns.index(term)
            dist = cosine(us[i,], vs[user])
            if(dist > 0):
                values[columns[i][0]] = dist
    values = sorted(values.items(), key=lambda kv: kv[1])[0:numWords]
    return(values)

Building Social Networks from Lexical Data¶

In the following section, we'll build networks based on the structure of the user's tweets. What will result from that is a network that isn't constructed by hard connections (like following or retweeting) but on the similarities of their latent semantic output. I think of these as potential connections that are reinforced in many cases by hard connections; seeing these connections and finding those nodes that connect groups will allow us to better understand how information is transmitted. It can explain why someone followed a particular user or how they heard about a particular thing. We build these networks by first finding the n most similar users to the given user, then finding the n most similar to each of the users that we start with.

Building a network based on a username

We'll begin by building a network based on a username, TEN_GOP.

In [11]:
def buildNetwork(user, numUsers, v=np.genfromtxt("v.csv", delimiter=','),
                 s=np.genfromtxt("s.csv", delimiter=','), users = pd.read_csv("users.csv"),
                 network = nx.Graph()):
    sn = user
    nodes = userToAll(v,s, user, numUsers, users)
    for edge in nodes:
        network.add_edge(sn, edge[0], weight=edge[1])
        secondaryNodes = userToAll(v,s, edge[0], numUsers, users)
        for sec in secondaryNodes:
            network.add_edge(edge[0], sec[0], weight=sec[1])
    return(network)
In [12]:
g = buildNetwork("TEN_GOP", 30, v, s, users)

These kinds of illustrations are good for demonstratingthe extent of a network and its interconnectedness. It also shows us from which nodes many of the connections originate (see TEN_GOP or the node starting with 79800b0f72 on the left). Now that we have a graph, though, it's more useful to run some metrics. We're interested in finding bridge nodes and that means we want to look at the betweeness centrality. Networkx has a nice function for determining this; we'll use the current flow betweeness as it's designed to simulate the flow of information across a network. Let's get the ten most central nodes.

Networks based on a Word

What does the network of people most similar to the term republican look like?

In [25]:
def buildWordNetwork(term, numUsers,columns, u=np.genfromtxt("u.csv", delimiter=','),
                     v=np.genfromtxt("v.csv", delimiter=','),
                    s=np.genfromtxt("s.csv", delimiter=','),
                    users = pd.read_csv("users.csv"),
                    network = nx.Graph()):
    nodes = wordToAllUsers(u,s,v, term, columns, numUsers, users)
    sn = nodes[0][0]
    for edge in nodes:
        network.add_edge(sn, edge[0], weight=edge[1])
        secondaryNodes = userToAll(v,s, edge[0], numUsers, users)
        for sec in secondaryNodes:
            network.add_edge(edge[0], sec[0], weight=sec[1])
    return(network)
